{{nihongo foot|'''''Dragon Slayer: The Legend of Heroes'''''|ドラゴンスレイヤー 英雄伝説|Doragon Sureiyā Eiyū Densetsu|lead=yes|group=lower-alpha}} is a 1989 [[role-playing game]] developed by [[Nihon Falcom]]. It is the sixth game in the ''[[Dragon Slayer (series)|Dragon Slayer]]'' series and the first in ''[[The Legend of Heroes]]'' franchise.

It was originally released in 1989 for the [[NEC PC-8801]]. Within the next few years, it would also be ported to the [[NEC PC-9801]], [[MSX|MSX 2]], [[PC Engine CD-ROM]]/[[TurboGrafx-CD]], [[Sharp X68000]], [[Sega Mega Drive]], and [[Super Famicom]]. A ''Dragon Slayer: The Legend of Heroes'' [[Barcode Battler]] card set was also released by [[Epoch Co.]] in 1992. The PC Engine version was released in the [[United States]] for the TurboGrafx-CD and was the only game in the series released in the US until ''[[The Legend of Heroes: A Tear of Vermillion]]'', the [[PlayStation Portable]] [[Video game remake|remake]].

In 1995, a version of the game was broadcast exclusively for Japanese markets via the Super Famicom's [[Satellaview]] subunit under the name ''BS Dragon Slayer Eiyu Densetsu''. In 1998, a remake of ''The Legend of Heroes'' was bundled with a remake of ''[[Dragon Slayer: The Legend of Heroes II]]'' and was released for both the [[PlayStation]] and [[Sega Saturn]].

==Reception==
The PC Engine version was rated 25.24 out of 30 by ''[[PC Engine Fan]]'' magazine.<ref>{{cite journal |title=ROLEPLAYING GAME |journal=[[PC Engine Fan]] |issue=PC Engine All Catalog '92: PC Engine Fan Appendix |date=August 1992 |language=ja |pages=33-48 (42-3) |url=https://archive.org/details/pc-engine-all-catalog-92-pc-engine-fan-appendix-august-1992/PC%20Engine%20All%20Catalog%20%2792%20-%20PC%20Engine%20Fan%20Appendix%20%28August%201992%29/page/42/mode/2up}}</ref> ''[[Famitsu]]'' scored the PC Engine CD-ROM version 29 out of 40 in 1991.<ref name="Fam">{{Cite web |title=ドラゴンスレイヤー 英雄伝説 [PCエンジン] |url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=11970 |url-status=deviated |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130627092718/http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=11970 |archive-date=2013-06-27 |website=ファミ通.com |language=ja}}</ref> They later scored the Super Famicom version 29 out of 40 in 1992,<ref name="SFC">{{cite web|url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=9222|title=ドラゴンスレイヤー 英雄伝説 [スーパーファミコン] / ファミ通.com|publisher=famitsu |language=ja}}</ref> and the Sega Mega Drive version 23 out of 40 in 1994.<ref name="SMD">{{cite web|url=http://www.famitsu.com/cominy/?m=pc&a=page_h_title&title_id=940|title=ドラゴンスレイヤー 英雄伝説 [メガドライブ] / ファミ通.com|publisher=famitsu |language=ja}}</ref>

In its January 1993 issue, ''[[Electronic Games]]'' magazine's Electronic Gaming Awards nominated the TurboGrafx-CD version for the 1992 [[List of Game of the Year awards|Multimedia Game of the Year]] award. They wrote it "demonstrates how far multimedia has come" since the same design team's ''[[Ys I & II]]'' and that this "mammoth quest is meticulously detailed and incorporates highly involved game play".<ref>{{cite journal|title=Electronic Gaming Awards|journal=Electronic Games|date=January 1993|issue=38|pages=26–7|url=http://archives.tg-16.com/00_happy_new_year_1993.htm|access-date=5 February 2012}}</ref>

